wdr:trigger-akademie-plato a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Plato founds his school in the grove Akademeia"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 387 BC Plato established his philosophical school in the grove Akademeia outside Athens. The school took the name of the place, and the place name thereby came to denote an institution of learning, the meaning carried into Latin academia and the modern languages."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q859 ;
    drift:eventDate "0387"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-alternativlos-merkel a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Angela Merkel's repeated use of 'alternativlos' 2009-2010"@en ;
    dct:description "Chancellor Merkel systematically used 'alternativlos' to justify the Euro rescue package, health reform, and Stuttgart 21, prompting the Gesellschaft fuer deutsche Sprache to name it Unwort des Jahres 2010."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-ampere-electrodynamics a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Ampere founds electrodynamics"@en ;
    dct:description "From 1820 Andre-Marie Ampere formulated the laws relating electric current and magnetism, founding electrodynamics. His name was adopted for the unit of current at the 1881 International Electrical Congress."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q675 ;
    drift:eventDate "1820"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-angora-city a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Angora (Ancyra / Ankara), Turkey"@en ;
    dct:description "The long-haired goat and its wool took the name of Angora, the old form of Ancyra (modern Ankara); 'Angora goat' is attested 1745 and the wool sense by 1810, the city name standing for the material."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q3640 ;
    drift:eventDate "1745"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-arbeit-protestant a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Protestant Reformation and the valorisation of secular vocation (Beruf)"@en ;
    dct:description "Luther's concept of the Beruf (calling/vocation) and the Protestant ethic elevated secular labour to a morally dignified activity, helping transform Arbeit from mere toil to valued work."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q12562 ;
    drift:eventDate "1530"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-aspirin-bayer a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Bayer launches Aspirin brand"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1899 Bayer registered and marketed acetylsalicylic acid under the brand Aspirin. In several countries the trademark lapsed (in the United States it was ruled generic in 1921), and the brand name passed into common use as the name of the substance itself."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q152051 ;
    drift:eventDate "1899"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-assassin-crusades a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Crusader contact with the Nizari Ismailis"@en ;
    dct:description "During the Crusades the Nizari Ismaili order of Syria and Persia (active from c. 1090) became known to European chroniclers under the Arabic pejorative hashishin. Their reputation for targeted killing of political and military figures attached the killing sense to the name; later legend, popularised by Marco Polo, reinforced it."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1192"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-atlas-mercator a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Mercator's 'Atlas' map collection (1595)"@en ;
    dct:description "Gerardus Mercator titled his posthumously completed 1595 collection of maps 'Atlas', invoking the Titan who bore the heavens, and its frontispiece depicted the figure. The work's fame fixed 'atlas' as the common word for a bound book of maps, an English usage attested from 1636."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q6353 ;
    drift:eventDate "1595"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-attack-polysemy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual polysemous extension of 'attack' across the 20th century"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. Across the 20th century 'attack' extended from military/physical assault into medical, sporting and figurative domains. The cause is gradual polysemy and is undetermined; recorded here as a diffuse trigger so the change can be aligned with the SemEval signal without asserting a specific cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1950"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-backfisch-literatur a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Student slang origin and 19th c. spread via the Backfischroman"@en ;
    dct:description "DWDS records the figurative sense 'adolescent girl' as student slang from the mid-16th century. The genre of the 'Backfischroman' for young female readers later spread the figurative sense across the German-speaking public in the 19th century."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1550"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-bakelite-baekeland a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Baekeland markets Bakelite resin"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1909 Leo Baekeland announced and branded Bakelite, the first fully synthetic plastic. The brand became widely used as a loose generic label for hard moulded phenolic plastics of the era."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q243442 ;
    drift:eventDate "1909"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-ball-polysemy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual polysemous extension of 'ball' across the 20th century"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The distribution of 'ball' across its object, social-dance and figurative senses shifted gradually; the cause is undetermined polysemy. Recorded as a diffuse trigger so the change can be aligned with the SemEval signal without asserting a specific cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1950"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-banause-bildung a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Neo-humanist cult of Bildung, late 18th to 19th century"@en ;
    dct:description "The neo-humanist revival of Greek learning and the 19th c. ideal of Bildung made the Greek 'banausos' a learned term of contempt. In German educated usage 'Banause' narrowed to a person without taste or appreciation for art and the intellect."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1800"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-based-lilb a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Lil B's reappropriation of 'based' (c. 2010)"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 2010 the rapper Lil B redefined 'based', previously a drug-related slur, to mean being positive and true to oneself; internet communities then spread it as a term of approval."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-becquerel-radioactivity a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Becquerel's discovery of radioactivity"@en ;
    dct:description "Henri Becquerel discovered natural radioactivity in 1896, sharing the 1903 Nobel Prize in Physics with the Curies. His name was adopted for the SI unit of radioactivity in 1975 at the 15th General Conference on Weights and Measures."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q41269 ;
    drift:eventDate "1896"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-bikini-tests a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Operation Crossroads nuclear tests at Bikini Atoll"@en ;
    dct:description "The United States conducted nuclear tests at Bikini Atoll in July 1946. Designer Louis Reard named his new swimsuit 'bikini' the same month, trading on the explosive notoriety of the place name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q569545 ;
    drift:eventDate "1946"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-billig-price a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Pejoration ueber die Preisbedeutung"@en ;
    dct:description "Kein einzelnes datierbares Ereignis. Ueber die Zwischenbedeutung 'preiswert' kippte 'billig' zur negativen Wertung 'minderwertig', als niedriger Preis mit geringer Qualitaet gleichgesetzt wurde. Das Ankerjahr ist eine repraesentative Belegstelle, keine Ursache."@de ;
    drift:eventDate "1850"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-biro-patent a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Laszlo Biro patents the ballpoint pen"@en ;
    dct:description "Laszlo Biro patented his ballpoint pen in 1938, and pens were marketed under the Biro name. In Britain and the Commonwealth the brand name became the ordinary word for any ballpoint pen."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q312680 ;
    drift:eventDate "1938"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-bit-binarydigit a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "coining of 'bit' (binary digit) and the rise of digital computing"@en ;
    dct:description "The term 'bit', a contraction of 'binary digit' attributed to John W. Tukey, appeared in print in Claude Shannon's 1948 paper 'A Mathematical Theory of Communication'. The subsequent spread of digital computing established the computing sense, broadening the word from 'a small piece' into a technical unit of information."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1948"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-blitz-london a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Blitz: German bombing campaign against Britain"@en ;
    dct:description "From September 1940 the German aerial bombing of Britain was named 'the Blitz' in English, clipped from 'Blitzkrieg'. The term then broadened to any sudden, intensive concentrated effort."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q6900329 ;
    drift:eventDate "1940"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-blm-movement a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Black Lives Matter movement"@en ;
    dct:description "The BLM movement, especially after 2013, mainstreamed 'woke' as a marker of social-justice awareness."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q19600530 ;
    drift:eventDate "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-bourbon-county a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Bourbon County, Kentucky"@en ;
    dct:description "American corn whiskey was first made in Bourbon County, Kentucky (organized 1785); the county name attached to the spirit, attested by 1840."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q486105 ;
    drift:eventDate "1840"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-bowdlerize-shakespeare a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Thomas Bowdler's 'Family Shakespeare' (1818)"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1818 Thomas Bowdler published an expurgated 'Family Shakespeare' with passages deemed indecent removed. His name became a verb (attested 1836) for the practice of purging text of supposedly offensive content."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1333546 ;
    drift:eventDate "1818"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-boykott-landleague a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Irish Land League ostracism of Captain Boycott"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1880 the Irish Land League organized a campaign of social and economic isolation against land agent Charles Boycott after he refused to lower rents. The action drew international press coverage and his surname became the common term for the tactic."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q455534 ;
    drift:eventDate "1880"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-braille-system a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Braille devises the raised-dot system"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1824 the fifteen-year-old Louis Braille devised a six-dot tactile code for reading and writing, published in 1829. The system spread internationally and took his name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q93182 ;
    drift:eventDate "1824"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-brutal-intensifier a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Colloquial bleaching of a cruelty word into an intensifier"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. 'Brutal' weakened in 20th-century colloquial speech from literal cruelty to a generic intensifier of harshness or unpleasantness (brutal weather, the brutal truth). The anchor year is a representative attestation of the intensifier use, not a cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1970"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-calico-calicut a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Cloth of Calicut (Kozhikode)"@en ;
    dct:description "Europeans first obtained the cotton cloth at the Malabar-coast port of Calicut (modern Kozhikode); the place name became the cloth name 'calico', attested in English from the 1530s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q28729 ;
    drift:eventDate "1530"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-canary-islands a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Songbird of the Canary Islands"@en ;
    dct:description "The finch native to the Canary Islands was called 'Canary-bird' (1570s) for its place of origin, then shortened to 'canary' (1650s). The islands' Latin name Insula Canaria ('island of dogs') is itself debated."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q5813 ;
    drift:eventDate "1570"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-cancel-callout a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Social-media call-out culture and #MeToo (2017)"@en ;
    dct:description "The 2017 surge of social-media accountability movements, especially #MeToo, popularised 'cancelling' public figures, fixing the new transitive sense of 'to cancel someone'."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-cardigan-balaclava a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Earl of Cardigan at the Charge of the Light Brigade"@en ;
    dct:description "The 7th Earl of Cardigan reportedly wore a knitted woollen jacket while leading the Charge of the Light Brigade at Balaclava in 1854 during the Crimean War. The garment took his name, attested as 'cardigan' by 1868."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q335449 ;
    drift:eventDate "1854"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-cassandra-troy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Cassandra, the unbelieved prophetess of Troy"@en ;
    dct:description "In Greek myth Apollo gave Cassandra the gift of prophecy, then cursed it so that, though she spoke truth, none would believe her; her warnings about the fall of Troy were ignored. The name has been used figuratively since the 1660s for an unheeded prophet of doom."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q170779 ;
    drift:eventDate "1660"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-cellophane-brand a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Cellophane brand film commercialised"@en ;
    dct:description "Jacques Brandenberger patented Cellophane and began commercial production of the transparent cellulose film around 1912 (perfected from his 1908 work). The brand became the ordinary word for the film; Wiktionary lists it among genericized trademarks."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q117187 ;
    drift:eventDate "1912"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-celsius-scale a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Celsius proposes the centigrade temperature scale"@en ;
    dct:description "Anders Celsius proposed a centigrade temperature scale in 1742. The unit was formally named 'degree Celsius' in 1948 by the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures, to honour him and avoid confusion with the centigrade angular measure."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q81130 ;
    drift:eventDate "1742"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-champagne-region a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Wine production in the Champagne province of France"@en ;
    dct:description "The former province of Champagne in northeast France gave its name to the wine made there; the term then narrowed to the sparkling wine produced by methode champenoise."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1660"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-chauvinismus-play a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Cogniard brothers' play 'La cocarde tricolore' (1831)"@en ;
    dct:description "The 1831 vaudeville 'La cocarde tricolore' by the Cogniard brothers popularized the figure of Chauvin as the archetype of bellicose, boastful patriotism. From this the French 'chauvinisme' was coined (1843) and Latinized into German as 'Chauvinismus'."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1798716 ;
    drift:eventDate "1831"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-circle-polysemy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual polysemous extension of 'circle' across the 20th century"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The social-group sense of 'circle' gained relative weight gradually; the cause is undetermined polysemy. Recorded as a diffuse trigger so the change can be aligned with the SemEval signal without asserting a specific cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1950"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-cologne-eau a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Production of eau de Cologne"@en ;
    dct:description "From 1709 a scented water marketed as 'eau de Cologne' was produced in the city. Its fame fixed the city name as the English word for a light perfume."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q365 ;
    drift:eventDate "1709"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-covid a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "COVID-19 pandemic"@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q81068910 ;
    drift:eventDate "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Pandemic .

wdr:trigger-cravat-croats a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Croat cavalry in the Thirty Years War"@en ;
    dct:description "Croat (Crabat) light cavalry fighting for the Catholic League wore linen neck scarves. The fashion was imitated in France from the 1650s, and the ethnonym 'cravate' became the name of the garment."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1650"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-cringe-memeculture a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Social-media meme culture (2010s, r/cringe)"@en ;
    dct:description "Merriam-Webster records the slang adjective from 1983. Online meme and reaction culture, including the r/cringe subreddit (founded 2011) and the 'cringe compilation' video genre, spread the predicative adjective/noun use widely in the 2010s but did not coin it."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-culture-wars a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "US culture-war polarisation (2019-)"@en ;
    dct:description "Conservative politicians and media adopted 'woke' as a derisive label for progressive excess, completing the reversal."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-curie-radioactivity a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Curies' discovery of radium"@en ;
    dct:description "Pierre and Marie Curie discovered radium and polonium in 1898 and pioneered the study of radioactivity. The unit of radioactivity was named in honour of Pierre Curie, first attested 1910."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q37463 ;
    drift:eventDate "1898"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-currant-corinth a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Corinth raisin trade"@en ;
    dct:description "Small dried grapes were exported from Corinth as 'raisins of Corauntz'. The place name was clipped to 'currant', with the final -s reanalysed as a plural ending, and became the fruit name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q103011 ;
    drift:eventDate "1500"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-dahlia-cavanilles a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Cavanilles names the genus Dahlia for Anders Dahl"@en ;
    dct:description "The Spanish botanist Antonio Jose Cavanilles named the genus Dahlia in 1791 in honour of the Swedish botanist Anders Dahl. The English word is attested by 1804."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q496775 ;
    drift:eventDate "1791"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-dalmatian-region a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Dalmatia region"@en ;
    dct:description "The spotted carriage dog was called 'Dalmatian dog' (1810), presumably for Dalmatia, and shortened to 'dalmatian' by 1893. Whether the breed truly originates in the region is debated among breeders."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q528042 ;
    drift:eventDate "1810"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-damast-damaskus a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Figured cloth from Damascus"@en ;
    dct:description "The patterned figured silk traded from Damascus carried the city name. Through Italian Damasco it entered German as Damast from the late medieval period."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q3766 ;
    drift:eventDate "1400"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-denim-nimes a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Textile production at Nimes"@en ;
    dct:description "The serge cloth exported as 'serge de Nimes' carried the city name. English speakers clipped the phrase to 'de Nim' and reanalysed it as the fabric name 'denim'."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q42807 ;
    drift:eventDate "1695"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-diesel-patent a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Rudolf Diesel's engine patent"@en ;
    dct:description "Rudolf Diesel patented his compression-ignition engine (German patent filed 1892, granted 1893) and published the design in 1893. The engine and, later, its fuel were named after the inventor, turning his surname into a generic technical term."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q12674 ;
    drift:eventDate "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-doomscrolling-covid a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "COVID-19 pandemic"@en ;
    dct:description "The 2020 COVID-19 pandemic, with its constant stream of alarming news, drove an explosion in the use of 'doomscrolling'; Merriam-Webster added it to its watch list and dictionary in 2020."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q81068910 ;
    drift:eventDate "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Pandemic .

wdr:trigger-draconian-code a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Draco's Athenian law code (c. 621 BC)"@en ;
    dct:description "The Athenian lawgiver Draco issued the city's first written code around 621 BC, notorious for prescribing death for even minor offences. The proverbial severity of these laws gave English 'draconian', which generalized to mean any disproportionately harsh measure."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "0621"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-edge-polysemy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual polysemous extension of 'edge' across the 20th century"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The figurative senses of 'edge' (advantage, tension, frontier of innovation) gained relative weight gradually; the cause is undetermined polysemy. Recorded as a diffuse trigger so the change can be aligned with the SemEval signal without asserting a specific cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1950"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-egregious-irony a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Ironic reversal of a term of praise"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The positive 'distinguished' was applied ironically (egregiously bad), and the ironic, negative sense displaced the original within a few decades in the later 16th century. The anchor year is the earliest negative attestation, not a cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1573"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-escalator-otis a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Otis markets the Escalator brand"@en ;
    dct:description "The Otis Elevator Company introduced and trademarked the moving stairway under the brand Escalator around 1900. Widespread use of the brand as the ordinary name for moving stairways led a 1950 trademark ruling to find the word generic."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1134069 ;
    drift:eventDate "1900"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-etappe-generaluse a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual 19th-century generalisation of military 'Etappe'"@en ;
    dct:description "DWDS records the military supply-zone sense from around 1700 and a generalised 'Tagesmarsch, Streckenabschnitt' (day's march, section of route) and figurative 'Zeit-, Entwicklungsabschnitt' (stage, phase) developing through the 19th century. No single datable event is recorded; the cause is gradual generalisation of the military term into everyday usage."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1850"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-face-polysemy a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "gradual polysemous extension of 'face' across the 20th century"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The figurative and surface senses of 'face' gained relative weight gradually; the cause is undetermined polysemy. Recorded as a diffuse trigger so the change can be aligned with the SemEval signal without asserting a specific cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1950"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-fahrenheit-scale a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Fahrenheit invents the mercury thermometer and scale"@en ;
    dct:description "Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit invented the mercury-in-glass thermometer and proposed his temperature scale in 1714. The scale came to be named after him, first attested as the word 'fahrenheit' in 1753."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q57073 ;
    drift:eventDate "1714"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-fascism-mussolini a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Rise of Mussolini's Fasci and the March on Rome"@en ;
    dct:description "Mussolini founded the Fasci Italiani di Combattimento in 1919; the 1922 March on Rome brought the movement to power. English borrowed 'fascism' as its proper name, then broadened it to far-right authoritarianism generally."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q468823 ;
    drift:eventDate "1922"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-filterblase-pariser a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Eli Pariser, 'The Filter Bubble' (2011)"@en ;
    dct:description "Eli Pariser's 2011 book 'The Filter Bubble' coined the concept; the German loan-translation 'Filterblase' became the standard term for algorithmic information isolation in German media debate."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q111687183 ;
    drift:eventDate "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-foehn-de-brand a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Sanitas registers the Foen hair-dryer brand"@en ;
    dct:description "The company Sanitas registered the trademark Foen for its electric hair dryer in 1909 (first model 1908). After AEG acquired Sanitas the brand persisted, and the word became the ordinary German term for any hair dryer."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1909"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-frankenstein-shelley a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Mary Shelley's 'Frankenstein' (1818)"@en ;
    dct:description "Mary Shelley's novel 'Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus' (1818) told of a scientist whose animated creature turns against him. The name generalized to mean a creation that overpowers and destroys its creator, and (by popular confusion) the creature itself, attested figuratively from the 1830s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q150827 ;
    drift:eventDate "1818"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-frankfurter-frankfurt a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Sausage of Frankfurt am Main"@en ;
    dct:description "A smoked sausage associated with Frankfurt am Main; German 'Frankfurter Wurst' was adopted in American English as 'frankfurter' (attested 1894), the city name standing for the product."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1794 ;
    drift:eventDate "1894"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-frau-leveling a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Soziale Generalisierung eines Standestitels"@en ;
    dct:description "Kein einzelnes datierbares Ereignis. 'Frau' verlor ueber Jahrhunderte den exklusiven Adelsbezug und wurde zur allgemeinen Bezeichnung jeder erwachsenen Frau, waehrend 'Weib' absank. Das Ankerjahr markiert die etablierte allgemeine Bedeutung, keine Ursache."@de ;
    drift:eventDate "1700"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-fromm-luther a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Luther's Bible translation 1522-1534"@en ;
    dct:description "Luther's translation systematically used 'fromm' for the biblical concept of God-fearing righteousness, transposing the word into the religious sphere and displacing its earlier general sense of capability."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1571095 ;
    drift:eventDate "1522"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-front-wwi a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "First World War static trench warfare 1914-1918"@en ;
    dct:description "The static line warfare of the First World War (1914-1918) fixed 'die Front' as the term for the combat zone in everyday German. From this war usage the word broadened to any line of confrontation, political or meteorological."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q361 ;
    drift:eventDate "1914"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-fuchsia-plumier a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Plumier names the genus Fuchsia for Leonhart Fuchs"@en ;
    dct:description "The French botanist Charles Plumier named the genus Fuchsia in 1703 in honour of the German botanist Leonhart Fuchs. The English word is attested by 1753, and the colour sense by 1921."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q60756 ;
    drift:eventDate "1703"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-funk-genre a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "emergence of funk music"@en ;
    dct:description "The rise of funk as an African-American music genre (James Brown et al.) carried the word from 'bad smell' to a marker of style and soul."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q164444 ;
    drift:eventDate "1965"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-galvanisieren-frogleg a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Galvani's bioelectricity experiments"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 1791 Luigi Galvani published experiments on the twitching of frog-leg muscles under electric stimulation. The German verb formed from his name first meant to treat with current, then broadened to electroplating and figurative rousing."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1589 ;
    drift:eventDate "1791"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-galvanize-frogleg a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Galvani's bioelectricity experiments"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 1791 Luigi Galvani published experiments showing that frog-leg muscles twitch when touched by metal, which he attributed to 'animal electricity'. The verb derived from his name first meant to stimulate by current, then broadened to mean rousing into action."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1589 ;
    drift:eventDate "1791"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-gargantuan-rabelais a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Rabelais's 'Gargantua' (1534)"@en ;
    dct:description "Francois Rabelais's comic novel 'La Vie tres horrifique du grand Gargantua' (1534) centred on a giant of prodigious size and appetite. The character's fame made 'gargantuan' an English adjective for the enormous, attested from the 1590s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q822290 ;
    drift:eventDate "1534"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-gaslighting-politics a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Political and media discourse surge (2016-2018)"@en ;
    dct:description "From the 2016 US election onward, commentators applied 'gaslighting' to political messaging and misinformation, broadening it from a clinical term to a general label for deceptive manipulation; Merriam-Webster reported a steep lookup and usage rise."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
