    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-granola-brand a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Granola registered as a cereal brand"@en ;
    dct:description "The name Granola was registered as a breakfast-cereal trademark around 1886 (a respelling of the earlier Granula). After the trademark lapsed the word passed into general use for any oat-based baked cereal."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1886"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-guillotine-revolution a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Proposal and adoption of the beheading machine in the French Revolution"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1789 deputy Joseph-Ignace Guillotin proposed that capital punishment use a uniform mechanical device. The machine was adopted in 1792 during the French Revolution and was named after him by metonymy, despite his opposition to the eponym."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q220650 ;
    drift:eventDate "1792"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-gutmensch-unwort a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Gutmensch chosen as Unwort des Jahres 2015"@en ;
    dct:description "In January 2016 a language-critical jury named Gutmensch the non-word of 2015, reflecting how the term had become a right-wing polemical weapon to dismiss liberal opponents."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-guy-gunpowder a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Gunpowder Plot of Guy Fawkes"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1605 Guy Fawkes was caught guarding explosives beneath the English Parliament in the Gunpowder Plot. The annual burning of his effigy ('a guy') on 5 November fixed his name to a grotesque figure, from which the broadened modern sense 'man, fellow' later developed."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q13898 ;
    drift:eventDate "1605"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-halcyon-alcyone a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Alcyone and the calm of the halcyon days"@en ;
    dct:description "In Greek myth Alcyone, daughter of Aeolus, was changed into a kingfisher; the gods stilled the winter seas for fourteen halcyon days while she nested. The legend (transmitted through Ovid and the medieval bestiaries) fixed the bird-name as a figure for calm, fixing the adjective by the 1540s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q912904 ;
    drift:eventDate "1540"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-hamburger-hamburg a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Hamburg steak named for the city of Hamburg"@en ;
    dct:description "The chopped-beef 'Hamburg steak' (attested by 1880) carried the name of the German port of Hamburg; 'hamburger' then narrowed to the sandwich (by 1909). The reason the city is invoked is not firmly established in the sources."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1055 ;
    drift:eventDate "1880"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-harpy-harpies a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Harpies of Greek myth"@en ;
    dct:description "The Harpies of Greek myth, whose name means 'snatchers', were winged monsters that seized and fouled food. The figure entered English by the late 14th century, and the extended sense of a repulsively greedy or grasping person is recorded from about 1400."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q181360 ;
    drift:eventDate "1400"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-heimat-romantik a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "German Romanticism and 19th c. nationalism"@en ;
    dct:description "From around 1800 the Romantic movement and the subsequent national awakening invested 'Heimat' with sentimental and ideological meaning, turning a legal-territorial term into a concept of emotional belonging and origin."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1800"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-herculean-labours a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Myth of Hercules and the Twelve Labours"@en ;
    dct:description "Hercules (Greek Herakles) was the archetypal hero of superhuman strength, set the Twelve Labours as penance. His legend, transmitted through classical literature, made 'herculean' an adjective for any task of extraordinary difficulty or any feat of great power, attested in English around 1600."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1590"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-hermetic-hermes a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Hermes Trismegistus and the hermetic seal"@en ;
    dct:description "Hermes Trismegistus, the legendary sage identified by alchemists with the god Hermes, was credited with a secret process for sealing a glass tube perfectly airtight. From this 'hermetic seal' the adjective acquired its everyday sense 'airtight', attested in the adverb from about 1600."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q192358 ;
    drift:eventDate "1600"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-hertz-waves a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Hertz demonstrates electromagnetic waves"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1888 Heinrich Hertz experimentally produced and detected electromagnetic (radio) waves, confirming Maxwell's theory. His name was adopted for the unit of frequency, formally ratified by the IEC in 1935 and the General Conference on Weights and Measures in 1960."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q41257 ;
    drift:eventDate "1888"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-hooligan-press a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "London press police-court reports of summer 1898"@en ;
    dct:description "In the summer of 1898 London newspaper police-court reports popularized 'Hooligan', probably from the comic-Irish surname Houlihan, as the label for unruly street youths. The proper-name origin generalized rapidly into a common noun for any violent young troublemaker."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1898"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-impfgegner-covid a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "COVID-19-Impfdebatte"@de,
        "COVID-19 vaccination debate (2020-2021)"@en ;
    dct:description "The 2020-2021 public debate over COVID-19 vaccination sharply politicised 'Impfgegner', loading the descriptive term with a derogatory, conflict-laden charge; DWDS shows a steep frequency rise."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q81068910 ;
    drift:eventDate "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Pandemic .

wdr:trigger-influencer-instagram a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Rise of Instagram and influencer marketing (mid-2010s)"@en ;
    dct:description "The growth of Instagram (launched 2010) and the surrounding creator economy turned 'influencer' into a job title for paid social-media promoters, narrowing the generic sense to this commercial meaning by the mid-2010s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q209330 ;
    drift:eventDate "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-jeans-genoa a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Genoese cloth trade"@en ;
    dct:description "Genoa (French Genes) was the European source of a sturdy fustian cloth. The fabric carried the city name into English as 'jean'; the trousers cut from it later took the same name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1449 ;
    drift:eventDate "1567"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-jingoism-song a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "G. W. Hunt's 1878 music-hall song during the Russo-Turkish crisis"@en ;
    dct:description "During the 1877-1878 crisis over British intervention against Russia, G. W. Hunt's music-hall song popularized by G. H. MacDermott carried the refrain 'we don't want to fight but by jingo if we do'. Supporters were dubbed 'jingoes' and 'jingoism' became a contemptuous label for belligerent patriotism."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1878"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Media .

wdr:trigger-joule-heat a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Joule's work on the mechanical equivalent of heat"@en ;
    dct:description "James Prescott Joule established the mechanical equivalent of heat in the 1840s, a foundation of the conservation of energy. His name was coined as the unit of electrical energy in 1882."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q8962 ;
    drift:eventDate "1843"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-jovial-jove a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Astrological disposition of those born under Jupiter"@en ;
    dct:description "Renaissance astrology held that those born under the sign of Jupiter (Jove), the most benign planet, were of a happy and generous disposition. The planetary adjective and the merry sense both surface in the 1580s, the cheerful meaning growing directly out of the astrological belief."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1580"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-kafkaesque-prozess a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Posthumous publication of Kafka's novels ('Der Prozess', 1925)"@en ;
    dct:description "Franz Kafka's novels, including 'Der Prozess' (The Trial), published posthumously from 1925, depicted individuals trapped in opaque, irrational bureaucratic systems. As their reputation spread in the 1930s and 1940s, 'Kafkaesque' came to mean oppressively absurd, bureaucratic, and disorienting, beyond mere reference to the author."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q905 ;
    drift:eventDate "1925"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-kaiser-augustus a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Establishment of the Roman imperial title under Augustus"@en ;
    dct:description "From 27 BC onward Octavian, the adopted heir of Julius Caesar, carried Caesar as part of his name and ruled as the first Roman emperor. His successors adopted Caesar as a standing element of the imperial titulature, converting the family name into a title of office; Germanic peoples borrowed it early as Kaisar/Kaiser."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1405 ;
    drift:eventDate "0027"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-kamikaze-leyte a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Japanese kamikaze suicide attacks in the Pacific War"@en ;
    dct:description "Beginning at the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944, organised Japanese suicide air attacks brought 'kamikaze' into English; the term later broadened to a figurative adjective for reckless self-destruction."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q308999 ;
    drift:eventDate "1944"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-kavalier-hofkultur a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Baroque court culture and the Kavalierstour, 17th century"@en ;
    dct:description "Baroque court society and the educational grand tour of young nobles (the Kavalierstour) made the 'Kavalier' the model of polished courtly manners. The word broadened from a mounted noble to any man of courteous, chivalrous bearing."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1650"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-kelvin-absolute-scale a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Thomson devises the absolute temperature scale"@en ;
    dct:description "William Thomson proposed an absolute thermodynamic temperature scale in 1848. After he was ennobled as Baron Kelvin, the unit increment of thermodynamic temperature was renamed 'kelvin' in 1967 at the 13th General Conference on Weights and Measures."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q122701 ;
    drift:eventDate "1848"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-ketzer-albigensian a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Albigensian Crusade against the Cathars"@en ;
    dct:description "Pope Innocent III launched the Albigensian Crusade in 1209 to suppress the Cathar sect. The sustained inquisitorial campaign made the group name (Latin Cathari, German Katzer/Ketzer) the standard word for heretics in general."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q51657 ;
    drift:eventDate "1209"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-klasse-marx a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "1848 socialist movement and Marx's Das Kapital (1867)"@en ;
    dct:description "The Communist Manifesto of 1848 and Marx's Das Kapital (1867) gave 'Klasse' a precise socio-economic meaning, the social class defined by its relation to the means of production. The socialist labour movement spread this technical sense in German."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q9061 ;
    drift:eventDate "1848"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-kleenex-kc a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Kimberly-Clark launches Kleenex"@en ;
    dct:description "Kleenex disposable facial tissue was introduced in 1924 (Cellucotton Products Co.; the Kleenex trademark is now held by Kimberly-Clark). The brand became so dominant that the name began to be used for any paper tissue, a usage the company has since fought to limit."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1741634 ;
    drift:eventDate "1924"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-klimakleber-lg a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Letzte Generation street-blockade campaign from January 2022"@en ;
    dct:description "From 24 January 2022 the Letzte Generation began gluing themselves to streets in Berlin. The Bild newspaper coined 'Klimakleber' as a pejorative. By 2023 activists began using the term themselves, initiating partial reappropriation."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q110819215 ;
    drift:eventDate "2022"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-krass-jugendsprache a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Jugendsprachliche Aufwertung eines Negativworts"@en ;
    dct:description "Kein einzelnes datierbares Ereignis. In der Jugendsprache seit den 1980er Jahren wurde 'krass' vom negativen 'extrem schlimm' zu einem allgemeinen, oft positiven Verstaerker. Das Ankerjahr ist eine repraesentative Belegstelle, keine Ursache."@de ;
    drift:eventDate "1985"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-labello-de-brand a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Beiersdorf introduces Labello"@en ;
    dct:description "Beiersdorf introduced the Labello lip-care stick in 1909. The brand became so dominant in German-speaking markets that the name is colloquially used for any lip balm."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q201691 ;
    drift:eventDate "1909"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-labyrinth-crete a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "The Cretan Labyrinth of Daedalus and the Minotaur"@en ;
    dct:description "In Greek myth Daedalus built the Labyrinth on Crete, a maze so intricate that the Minotaur could not escape it. The name, in English from about 1400 for the maze, yielded by the 1540s the figurative sense of any bewildering, intricate situation."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q48963 ;
    drift:eventDate "1540"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-laconic-sparta a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Reputation of Laconian (Spartan) terseness"@en ;
    dct:description "Classical writers recorded the Laconians of Sparta as famously curt of speech. Renaissance humanists revived the adjective 'laconic' from the region name to mean terse expression."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1580"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-lazarett-venice a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Founding of the Venetian Lazzaretto Vecchio"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1423 Venice converted the island of Santa Maria di Nazaret into a permanent plague hospital and quarantine station, the Lazzaretto Vecchio. The island name (blended with St Lazarus) generalised into a common noun for an isolation hospital and spread into German as Lazarett."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1423"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Pandemic .

wdr:trigger-leotard-trapeze a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Jules Leotard performs the flying trapeze in a close-fitting garment"@en ;
    dct:description "Jules Leotard, the popular French trapeze artist, performed in a close-fitting one-piece garment. After his death the garment was named for him, attested as 'leotards' by 1881."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q356388 ;
    drift:eventDate "1859"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-lesbian-sappho a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Sappho of Lesbos and her reception"@en ;
    dct:description "The poet Sappho of Lesbos wrote of love between women. Nineteenth-century reception of her verse turned the island adjective 'Lesbian' into a term for female same-sex desire."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q17892 ;
    drift:eventDate "1870"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-linoleum-walton a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Walton markets Linoleum floor covering"@en ;
    dct:description "Frederick Walton coined and registered Linoleum around 1864 for his linseed-oil floor covering. Because he did not police the term, it was held to have become generic in an 1878 English court ruling, one of the earliest recorded cases of trademark genericide."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q907886 ;
    drift:eventDate "1864"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-literally-bleaching a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Semantic bleaching of an assertive into an intensifier"@en ;
    dct:description "There is no single datable event. The intensifier use arose gradually in literary English from the 18th century onward, as a strong assertion of truth weakened into a generic emphasiser. The anchor year is a representative attestation point, not a cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1800"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-luddite-uprising a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Luddite machine-breaking uprisings"@en ;
    dct:description "Between 1811 and 1816 textile workers in the English Midlands and north destroyed mechanized looms and frames, fearing loss of livelihood. The movement, invoking the legendary Ned Ludd, gave its name first to the participants and later, by broadening, to any opponent of technology."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1159675 ;
    drift:eventDate "1811"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-luegenpresse-pegida a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "PEGIDA movement demonstrations, Dresden 2014"@en ;
    dct:description "From October 2014, PEGIDA demonstrators chanted 'Luegenpresse' at journalists, reactivating a Nazi-era slur and cementing its association with the far-right. Unwort des Jahres 2014."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q18762431 ;
    drift:eventDate "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-lunatic-luna a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Belief that the moon (Luna) caused recurring madness"@en ;
    dct:description "Medieval medicine, following classical sources, held that fits of insanity recurred with the phases of the moon (Latin luna). This belief produced Late Latin lunaticus 'moon-struck', borrowed into English by the late 13th century; the sense later broadened to wild folly."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1290"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-mach-de-shockwave a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Mach studies supersonic shock waves"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 1887 Ernst Mach photographed shock waves around projectiles moving faster than sound and described the relationship now expressed by the Mach number. The dimensionless number was named for him by Jakob Ackeret in 1929."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q93996 ;
    drift:eventDate "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-machiavellian-principe a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Machiavelli's 'Il Principe' (1532)"@en ;
    dct:description "Niccolo Machiavelli's treatise 'Il Principe', written 1513 and printed posthumously in 1532, advised rulers that the ends of holding power could justify deceit and cruelty. Its reception, often as a byword for amoral statecraft, made 'Machiavellian' a synonym for cunning and unscrupulous scheming in English from around 1600."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1399 ;
    drift:eventDate "1532"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-magenta-battle a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Battle of Magenta (1859)"@en ;
    dct:description "A brilliant crimson aniline dye introduced in 1860 was named in honour of the Battle of Magenta (1859), where French and Sardinian forces defeated the Austrians; the dye and colour took the battle's name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q681430 ;
    drift:eventDate "1859"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-malapropism-rivals a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Premiere of Sheridan's The Rivals"@en ;
    dct:description "Richard Brinsley Sheridan's comedy The Rivals premiered in 1775. Its character Mrs Malaprop habitually confused similar-sounding words; her name (from French 'mal a propos') became the term for such verbal blunders by metaphor."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q7760957 ;
    drift:eventDate "1775"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-marathon-olympics a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Marathon race at the 1896 Athens Olympics"@en ;
    dct:description "The first modern Olympics of 1896 staged a long-distance race commemorating the legendary run from the plain of Marathon to Athens after the 490 BC battle. The event fixed the ancient place name as the name of the race."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q8080 ;
    drift:eventDate "1896"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-masochism-sacher-masoch a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Sacher-Masoch's novels and Krafft-Ebing's coinage"@en ;
    dct:description "Leopold von Sacher-Masoch featured submission and pain in works such as 'Venus in Furs' (1869). The German neurologist Richard von Krafft-Ebing coined 'Masochismus' from his name in 1883; the English 'masochism' is attested by 1892."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q78474 ;
    drift:eventDate "1883"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-mauerfall a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Fall of the Berlin Wall (Mauerfall)"@en ;
    dct:description "The opening of the Berlin Wall on 9 November 1989 and the subsequent collapse of the GDR gave 'die Wende' its specific historical referent."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q69163529 ;
    drift:eventDate "1989"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-mausoleum-halicarnassus a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Construction of the tomb of Mausolus at Halicarnassus"@en ;
    dct:description "Around 353 to 351 BC a monumental tomb was built at Halicarnassus for Mausolus, satrap of Caria, and his sister-wife Artemisia. Its fame as one of the Seven Wonders made the ruler's name (Greek Mausoleion) the generic word for any grand tomb."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q296857 ;
    drift:eventDate "0353"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-maverick-cattle a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Samuel Maverick's unbranded Texas cattle"@en ;
    dct:description "Texas landowner Samuel A. Maverick was known for not branding his cattle, so unmarked strays came to be called 'mavericks' by the mid-1860s. The cattle sense broadened to mean any unattached, independent individual."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q346455 ;
    drift:eventDate "1867"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-mentor-telemaque a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Fenelon's 'Les Aventures de Telemaque' (1699)"@en ;
    dct:description "Mentor is a minor figure in Homer's Odyssey, but Francois Fenelon's enormously popular didactic romance 'Les Aventures de Telemaque' (1699) made Mentor the central wise counsellor to the young prince. The book's pan-European success turned the proper name into a common noun for a trusted adviser, attested in English from the mid eighteenth century."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q421615 ;
    drift:eventDate "1699"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-mercurial-mercury a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Astrological temperament of those born under Mercury"@en ;
    dct:description "Renaissance astrology held that people born under the planet Mercury were quick, lively, and changeable. The planetary adjective (attested late 14c.) acquired the temperament sense by the 1640s, reinforced by association with the fluid, ever-moving qualities of quicksilver (also called mercury)."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1640"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-mesmerize-mesmer a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Franz Mesmer's animal magnetism in vogue in Paris"@en ;
    dct:description "In the 1780s the physician Franz Mesmer popularised 'animal magnetism' as a healing practice in Paris. The verb 'mesmerize' was formed from his name to mean 'to hypnotise', then broadened by metaphor to 'captivate, fascinate'."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q160202 ;
    drift:eventDate "1784"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-monty-python-spam a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Monty Python's Flying Circus 'Spam' sketch (1970)"@en ;
    dct:description "The 1970 Monty Python sketch featuring 'Spam' repeated ad nauseam embedded the word's association with unwanted repetitive content in English geek culture, which internet users later applied to bulk email."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1777591 ;
    drift:eventDate "1970"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-morse-code-telegraph a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Morse and Vail develop the telegraph code"@en ;
    dct:description "From 1838 Samuel Morse and Alfred Vail developed the signalling code for the electric telegraph, publicly demonstrated in 1838 and used on the first US telegraph line in 1844. The code became known by Morse's name."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q75698 ;
    drift:eventDate "1838"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-narcissism-coinage a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Coinage of 'Narcissism' as a clinical term"@en ;
    dct:description "Havelock Ellis in 1898 compared a form of self-absorbed sexuality to the myth of Narcissus; in 1899 the German psychiatrist Paul Naecke coined 'Narzissmus' in 'Die sexuellen Perversitaeten'. The term entered English by 1905 and Freud's later work fixed its clinical sense, turning the mythic figure into a psychological category."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q552983 ;
    drift:eventDate "1899"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-naughty-weakening a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Gradual weakening of a moral condemnation"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. The strong moral sense 'wicked' weakened over the 17th century to the milder 'mischievous, disobedient', a common softening of moral terms when applied colloquially and to children. The anchor year is a representative attestation, not a cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1630"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-nemesis-goddess a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Greek goddess Nemesis"@en ;
    dct:description "Nemesis personified divine retribution in Greek religion, punishing arrogance and the disturbance of due proportion. Adopted into English as the name of the goddess, the word generalized to mean an instrument of inescapable downfall and then an unbeatable adversary."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1590"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-nicotine-tobacco a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Nicot introduces tobacco to the French court"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1560 Jean Nicot, French ambassador to Portugal, sent tobacco plants and seeds to the court in Paris. The plant genus Nicotiana was named for him, and the alkaloid isolated in 1828 took the name nicotine."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q318368 ;
    drift:eventDate "1560"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-notorious-collocation a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Pejoration by negative collocation"@en ;
    dct:description "No single datable event. 'Notorious' was repeatedly applied to bad or scandalous matters (notorious offenders, notorious crimes), and the negative collocations transferred their colour to the word over the late 16th century. The anchor year is a representative attestation, not a cause."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1593"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-nylon-dupont a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "DuPont announces nylon"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1938 DuPont publicly announced nylon, a coined name for its new synthetic polyamide fibre, deliberately left as a generic descriptor rather than a registered trademark. It rapidly became the ordinary word for the polymer and the products made from it."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q221062 ;
    drift:eventDate "1938"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-odyssey-homer a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Homer's epic poem the Odyssey"@en ;
    dct:description "Homer's Odyssey, the eighth-century BC epic of Odysseus's long voyage home from Troy, gave its title to English by 1600. The fame of that protracted, episodic journey produced the figurative common noun 'odyssey' for any long wandering, recorded from 1889."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q35160 ;
    drift:eventDate "1889"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Cultural .

wdr:trigger-ohm-de-law a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Ohm publishes Ohm's law"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1827 Georg Simon Ohm published 'Die galvanische Kette, mathematisch bearbeitet', stating the proportionality of current and voltage. His name became the unit of resistance, developed through the British Association unit work of the 1860s and internationally established in 1881 (per DWDS)."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1585 ;
    drift:eventDate "1827"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-ohm-law a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Ohm publishes Ohm's law"@en ;
    dct:description "In 1827 Georg Simon Ohm published 'Die galvanische Kette, mathematisch bearbeitet', stating the proportionality of current and voltage. His name was adopted for the unit of resistance by the British Association in the 1860s."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q1585 ;
    drift:eventDate "1827"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-orwellian-1984 a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Publication of Orwell's 'Nineteen Eighty-Four' (1949)"@en ;
    dct:description "George Orwell's novel 'Nineteen Eighty-Four', published in 1949, portrayed a surveillance state of perpetual war, thought control, and falsified history. Its immediate impact, deepened by Orwell's death in 1950, turned 'Orwellian' from a mere authorial adjective into a byword for oppressive state manipulation."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1949"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

