wdr:trigger-south-sea-bubble a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "the South Sea Bubble financial crisis (1720)"@en ;
    dct:description "The 1720 collapse of the South Sea Company's inflated share price, named the 'South Sea Bubble', fixed 'bubble' as the standard metaphor for a speculative market boom that bursts."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q18643921 ;
    drift:eventDate "1720"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Commercial .

wdr:trigger-stonewall a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Stonewall Riots and gay liberation movement"@en ;
    dct:description "The 1969 Stonewall Riots and subsequent gay liberation movement accelerated the reappropriation of 'gay' as a neutral/positive self-identifier."@en,
        "The 1969 Stonewall Riots and the subsequent gay liberation movement, including the founding of the Homosexuelle Aktion Westberlin in 1971, drove the reappropriation of 'schwul' as a neutral or positive self-identifier in German."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q51402 ;
    drift:eventDate "1969"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Political .

wdr:trigger-streaming-services a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "rise of broadband streaming media services"@en ;
    dct:description "Broadband internet and services such as YouTube (2005), Netflix streaming (2007) and Spotify (2008) made consuming audio and video as a continuous online flow mainstream, fixing the verb 'to stream' in the media sense."@en,
        "Broadband internet and services such as YouTube (2005), Netflix streaming (2007) and Spotify (2008) made consuming audio and video as a continuous online flow mainstream; German adopted 'streamen' for the media sense."@en ;
    owl:sameAs wd:Q866 ;
    drift:eventDate "2005"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

wdr:trigger-troll-usenet a drift:TriggerEvent ;
    rdfs:label "Usenet 'trolling for newbies' coinage (early 1990s)"@en ;
    dct:description "On Usenet around 1992, 'trolling' (from the fishing sense of trailing bait) named the practice of posting provocative messages to bait responses; the agent noun 'troll' followed and broadened across the social web."@en ;
    drift:eventDate "1992"^^xsd:gYear ;
    drift:triggerCategory drift:Technology .

